@node "Introduction" "Introduction"

  @{b}@{u} Introduction @{ub}@{uu}

Videomat is an easy to use video cassette management system. The maximum
number of video cassettes is only limited by the available storage space on
your disk.

Only a small amount of memory is needed, because only one cassette is hold
in memory at a time.

Videomat supports up to eight movies per cassette. This should be sufficient,
because it is nearly impossible to save more than 2 movies or more than
8 episodes of a series on a single video cassette.

The following items are stored:


  item                  example
  -----------------------------------------------------
  title of the movie    Curse of the Pink Panther
  series                Pink Panther
  topic                 crime, comedy
  kind                  movie
  country               GB
  director              Blake Edwards
  year of production    1983
  length in minutes     110
  date (record)         23.05.1996
  actors                Peter Sellers, David Niven, ...
  short description     ...


One can search for all of these items, for example to find all movies
of a certain actor.

Two kinds of printer output are supplied: a complete list or a form (like
the date entry form displayed on-screen). The printer output may be redirec-
ted to a disk file.

"Export" allows one to save either all cassettes or only the selected ones
to a sequential file. This is of use if one wants to import the data into a
database management system like SuperBase, for instance.

For details, have a look at the topics covered by this document.
@endnode


@node "Installation" "Installation"

  @{b}@{u} Installation @{ub}@{uu}

Just drag everything into a drawer of your choice.

(If you don't install any catalog file, English will be used as a default
language.)
@endnode


@node "Using" "Using the Software"

                            @{b}@{u} Using the Software @{ub}@{uu}


                       @{"     Create A New Project     " link "NewProject" 0}
                       @{"   Open An existing Project   " link "OldProject" 0}
                       @{"         Project menu         " link "Project-Menu" 0}
                       @{"          Edit menu           " link "Edit-Menu" 0}
@endnode


@node "NewProject" "Create A New Project"

  @{b}@{u} Create A New Project @{ub}@{uu}

To create a new project, select the @{"Input Data..." 0} item of the @{"Edit" link "Edit-Menu"0} menu.
An input form will be created. Don't enter anything - hit the @{"SAVE" 0} button
instead. Enter the name of the file to be created. Videomat will append the
extension @{i}.vid@{ui} and create the file.
@endnode


@node "OldProject" "Open An Existing Project"

  @{b}@{u} Open An Existing Project @{ub}@{uu}

To open an existing project, do one of the following:

 o  If one selects an item of the @{"Edit" link "Edit-Menu"0} menu, Videomat lets one
    specify a file name if this hasn't been done yet

 o  Select the item @{"Open..." 0} of the @{"Project" link "Project-Menu" 0} menu
@endnode


@node "Project-Menu" "Project Menu"

  @{b}@{u} Project Menu @{ub}@{uu}

The Project menu has the following items:

@{"Open..." 0}  This command lets one specify the name of the project file to
          be opened.

@{"About" 0}    The copyright notice is displayed.

@{"Quit..." 0}  Videomat will exit if one confirms the corresponding requester.
@endnode


@node "Edit-Menu" "Edit Menu"

  @{b}@{u} Edit Menu @{ub}@{uu}

The following items are offered by the Edit menu:

@{"Enter Data..." link "edit" 0}  displays the data entry form.

@{"Search..." link "search" 0}      opens the Search requester.

@{"Export..." link "export" 0}      allows one to export records to a sequential file.

@{"Print..." link "print" 0}       brings up the Print requester.
@endnode


@node "edit" "Enter Data..."

  @{b}@{u} Enter Data... @{ub}@{uu}

A data entry form is displayed where one can input data for up to eight
movies on a video cassette. Each movie is referenced by a so-called @{i}movie
number@{ui}, which can be altered by clicking the  arrowws (@{" < " 0}, @{" > " 0}) or by
entering a new movie # directly. (The movie number is displayed in the upper
right corner of the form).

The cassette can be selected by entering a cassette number into the text
field in the upper left corner of the window or by using the corresponding
arrows. Videomat will ignore all record numbers which are either lower than
1 or exceeding the current count of records in the project.

The buttons at the bottom of the window have the following meaning:


@{"EXIT" 0} closes the form without saving the altered data.

@{"SAVE" 0} saves the data and closes the form.

The following buttons cause the current data to be @{b}saved@{ub} before performing
any other action:

@{"|<<" 0}     goes to the first cassette.

@{"< <" 0}     decreases the cassette # by 10.

@{" < " 0}     goes to the previous record.

@{" > " 0}     goes to the next record, creating a new record if it doesn't exist.

@{"> >" 0}     increases the cassette # by 10.

@{">>|" 0}     goes to the last cassette.


One can enter the following data using Videomat's data entry form:


@{b}Title@{ub}        is the title of the movie.

@{b}Series@{ub}       is as a group title for several movies, for instance
             "Star Trek" or "Mr Bean".

@{b}Topic@{ub}        is used to store if the movie is "science-fiction",
             "comedy" or anything else.

@{b}Kind@{ub}         is "movie", "teleplay" or "animated cartoon".

@{b}Country@{ub}      is the name of the country there the movie has been
             created.

@{b}Director@{ub}     is the art director.

@{b}Year@{ub}         is the year the movie has been created in.

@{b}Length@{ub}       is the length of the movie, counted jn minutes.

@{b}Rec.Date@{ub}     is the day the movie has been recorded on.

@{b}Actors@{ub}       what do @{i}you@{ui} guess?.

@{b}Contents@{ub}     is a short description of the plot.
@endnode


@node "search" "Search..."

  @{b}@{u} Search... @{ub}@{uu}

The Search Dialogue uses the data entry form for entering the search crite-
ria. One can save and retrieve search criteria by clicking the @{"Open..." 0} and
@{"Save..." 0} buttons.

The search process is started by hitting @{"Start..." 0}; it is aborted by
hitting the @{"Cancel..." 0} button.

The result is displayed as a ListView gadget. These movies have been selec-
ted and can be exported or printed by clicking the @{"Export..." link "export" 0} or @{"Print..." link "print" 0}
button respectively.

One can edit a movie by clicking the corresponding entry of the list and
hitting the @{"Edit..."} button. To return to the search list, click @{i}EXIT@{ui}.

Click on the "Cancel" button to return to the Search Dialogue. One can start
a new search process, view the list by clicking the @{"List..."} button or
return to the main window by hitting @{"Cancel"}.
@endnode


@node "export" "Export..."

  @{b}@{u} Export... @{ub}@{uu}

@{b}Range@{ub}
One can export all movies, limit the output by a range of cassette numbers,
or export the movies selected by the @{"search process" link "search" 0} only.

@{b}Field delimiter@{ub}
One can change the character used to seperate individual fields of the
output. The default is ASCII 44, which is the comma (,).

@{b}File@{ub}
One can change the name of the file to be created. This defaults to the file
@{i}vm_SEQ.DAT@{ui}.

The remaining options allow one to quote all fields or to save the field
names (Actor, Director, and so on) in the first record.
@endnode


@node "print" "Print..."

  @{b}@{u} Print... @{ub}@{uu}

This command alows one to output the movie data to a printer.

The following options are available:

@{b}Print to:@{ub}
The printer output can be redirected to a disk file if one wishes so.

@{b}Range:@{ub}
One can print all records, a range of them or the movies selected by the
@{"search process" link "search" 0} only.

@{b}Format:@{ub}
One can select either List or Form.

 o  Form creates a formatted output which looks like the data entry form.
 o  List creates a list containing the cassette #, movie #, and movie
    title items only.

@{b}Options:@{ub}
One can have the fields seperated by TAB characters (ASCII 9) or filled
up with spaces to be fixed-lentgh.
@endnode


@node "System" "System Requirements"

  @{b}@{u} System Requirements @{ub}@{uu}

Videomat can run on all Amigas equipped with at least Kickstart 2.0.

The program has been tested on an Amiga 500 with Kickstart 2.1 and on an
Amiga 4000 with Kickstart 3.1 and 3.5.
@endnode


